{
    "analysis": "Previous metric-level analysis found many sustained faults across multiple nodes during 2021-03-23 06:30–07:00+08. The largest relative breach in metrics was the zabbix-agentd process metric on MG02/Tomcat02 (severity ≈ 1.33). However many KPIs simply equal their historical P95 (severity ≈ 1.0) across nodes, so metrics alone do not single out a single root cause component. According to the diagnosis workflow, the next step is trace analysis to determine which service/container is the most downstream faulty component in the call chain and to narrow the exact occurrence time for the single failure.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, perform anomaly detection based on global P95 thresholds computed from the full available trace series (no time filtering for threshold calc). Then filter to the incident window 2021-03-23 06:30:00 to 2021-03-23 07:00:00 (UTC+8) and find trace rows where value >= global_p95 for that (cmdb_id, trace_name). Aggregate these anomaly rows by cmdb_id and trace_name and return a compact summary limited to top 20 groups by anomaly_count with columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95. Also return the total number of trace anomaly rows found across the window. Only return the described aggregate table and the single total count."
}

{
    "analysis": "Trace-analysis found 505 trace anomaly rows in the incident window. The largest relative breaches are on dockerA2 → MG02/MG01 duration metrics (severity up to ~14.6), and there are modest row_count/duration anomalies between IG/Tomcat and MG/docker components. However, dockerA2 is not one of the allowed root-cause components in the provided list. Per the localization rules, when container-level traces implicate a non-listed container (dockerA2), we must map those trace anomalies to the downstream allowed service/node components (e.g., MG01/MG02, IG01/IG02, Tomcat01–04) and pick the most downstream faulty allowed component in the call chain. From previous metric faults, MG02 and Tomcat02/MG01 also show sustained faults; MG02 appears in both metric faults (zabbix process severity ≈1.33) and in trace anomalies (dockerA2→MG02 high duration severity). To confirm the root cause component and precise occurrence time, we should aggregate trace anomalies that point to allowed components and report counts, earliest anomaly timestamps, and max severity by target component. This will identify which allowed component is most implicated by trace anomalies and the earliest time the problem appears at that allowed component.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using trace.csv, recompute global P95 per (cmdb_id, trace_name) using the full series (no time filtering). Then filter trace.csv to the incident window 2021-03-23 06:30:00 to 2021-03-23 07:00:00 (UTC+8) and find anomaly rows where value >= global_p95 for that (cmdb_id, trace_name). From these anomaly rows, parse trace_name to detect target components in the allowed root-cause list [apache01, apache02, Tomcat01, Tomcat02, Tomcat03, Tomcat04, MG01, MG02, IG01, IG02, Mysql01, Mysql02, Redis01, Redis02] by matching patterns 'to_<COMP>' or 'from_<COMP>' (case-sensitive as in trace_name). Aggregate anomalies grouped by the matched allowed component and compute: matched_component, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, global_p95_for_that_trace_group (use the corresponding global_p95), severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95_for_that_trace_group. Return only the aggregate table sorted by anomaly_count desc (limit to top 20) and the total number of trace anomaly rows that matched any allowed component."}

{
    "analysis": "Trace-component mapping shows MG02 and MG01 are the most implicated allowed components by volume of trace anomalies (74 and 73 anomalies respectively). Tomcat02 also shows a notable relative breach (severity ≈1.42). Metric-level faults are widespread and many KPIs simply reached their historical P95 (severity≈1.0), while a few metrics (zabbix agent process on MG02/Tomcat02, some MySQL threads) show higher relative breaches. Metrics alone are ambiguous because many series are at P95 for the whole window. According to the diagnosis workflow we must now use targeted metric analysis for the top candidate allowed components to identify which resource KPI (CPU, memory, JVM load, disk, network, JVM OOM, etc.) first crossed thresholds and with the largest severity — this will guide the root cause reason. Logs showed no error logs earlier, so metrics are the primary signal now.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) from the full series (no time filtering). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2021-03-23 06:30:00 → 2021-03-23 07:00:00 (UTC+8) and find anomaly rows where value >= global_p95 for that (cmdb_id,kpi_name). Restrict results to the candidate components: [MG02, MG01, Tomcat02, Tomcat04, Tomcat03, Tomcat01, IG02, IG01, Mysql01, Mysql02]. Aggregate anomalies by cmdb_id and kpi_name and return a compact table (limit top 20 rows) with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window/global_p95. Also return the total number of anomaly rows matched to these candidate components. Sort the table by severity_ratio (desc) then anomaly_count (desc)."}
}

{
    "analysis": "The last step mapped trace anomalies to allowed components and found MG02 (74 anomalies) and MG01 (73 anomalies) as the most implicated by trace data; Tomcat02 also shows a notable relative breach (severity ≈ 1.42). Metric-level fault detection earlier flagged a zabbix-agentd process metric on MG02/Tomcat02 with the largest relative breach (~1.33), while many JVM/DB KPIs simply reached global P95 (severity≈1.0) for the full window. Combined, this suggests the problem likely involves MG01/MG02 (highest trace anomaly volume) and Tomcat02 (high relative metric breach). To determine the precise root cause component, occurrence time, and reason, we must now inspect resource-specific metric KPIs (CPU, memory, network, disk, JVM load, OOM indicators) for the top candidate components and find which KPI shows the earliest and strongest fault (highest severity_ratio and earliest fault start).",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) from the full available series (do not filter for the incident window when computing thresholds). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2021-03-23 06:30:00 → 2021-03-23 07:00:00 (UTC+8). Restrict analysis to the top candidate components [MG02, MG01, Tomcat02]. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) in that restricted set, find anomaly rows where value >= global_p95, then aggregate anomalies per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) producing: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_ts, latest_anomaly_ts, max_value_in_window, global_p95, severity_ratio = max_value_in_window / global_p95. Return the top 20 KPI groups sorted by severity_ratio (desc) then anomaly_count (desc). Also return the total number of anomaly rows matched to these three components. Limit output strictly to the described aggregate table and the single total count."
}

{
    "analysis": "The metric and trace analyses so far narrowed the problem to MG01, MG02, and Tomcat02. Metric-level faults show many sustained P95-level breaches across nodes, but the largest relative deviations (>>50%) are: MG01 OSLinux_NETWORK TCP-FIN-WAIT (severity=4.0) at 06:42→06:46 and MG02 OSLinux CPU SingleCpuidle (severity≈3.33) at 06:49. The zabbix-agentd process metric is persistently above P95 on MG02 and Tomcat02 but with modest severity (≈1.33) across the whole window, so it looks like a sustained condition rather than a sharp single failure. Trace anomalies concentrate on MG01/MG02 (highest counts) and indicate downstream impact on Tomcat/IG services. \n\nWhat can be derived now: the single most significant metric deviation that is earliest in the incident window is MG01 TCP-FIN-WAIT (start 2021-03-23 06:42:00+08) which is a strong candidate root cause signal (very high severity_ratio and indicates abnormal TCP connection states). MG02 CPU idle spike at 06:49 is later and also severe, suggesting either a secondary impact or another strong anomaly, but because the incident is described as a single failure we should prioritize the earliest, largest deviation to localize the root cause. \n\nWhat remains: confirm whether MG01 TCP state anomalies correspond to application-level impacts (traces and logs) and whether logs show any resource-level messages (network issues, disk errors, or JVM errors) around the 06:42 timestamp. Since error_logs.csv is empty and log.error_count was zero in top groups, we should inspect available log.csv entries (e.g., gc_pause, row_count, error_count, or other log features) for MG01, MG02, and Tomcat02 during the incident window to corroborate the metric-based hypothesis and to pick the exact root cause time and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using log.csv, filter rows to the incident window 2021-03-23 06:30:00 → 2021-03-23 07:00:00 (UTC+8) and restrict to components [MG01, MG02, Tomcat02]. Group the filtered rows by cmdb_id and log_name and compute: count, earliest timestamp, latest timestamp, and P95(value) (if value numeric). Return a compact table limited to the top 20 groups sorted by count (desc) with columns: cmdb_id, log_name, count, earliest_ts, latest_ts, p95_value. Also return the total number of log rows matched to these components in the window. Only return the described aggregate table and the single total count."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have followed the prescribed workflow: thresholds (global P95) computed from full series; metric anomaly detection and fault identification; trace mapping to allowed components; and log inspection. Current evidence: MG01 and MG02 are the most implicated allowed components (high trace anomaly volumes). Two node-level KPI faults stand out: MG01 OSLinux_NETWORK TCP-FIN-WAIT (severity_ratio = 2.0) with earliest anomaly at 2021-03-23 06:42:00+08, and MG02 OSLinux-CPU CPU-3 SingleCpuidle (severity_ratio ≈ 3.33) at 2021-03-23 06:49:00+08. Many other KPIs reached P95 across nodes for the whole window (sustained), including zabbix-agentd on MG02 and Tomcat02 (severity ≈ 1.33). \n\nWhat remains ambiguous: MG02 has the larger relative deviation but it occurs later (06:49), while MG01 shows an earlier, large TCP state anomaly (06:42) and high trace anomaly volume. Per the rules, for a single failure we should pick the predominant node fault — the one with strongest deviation and trace/log corroboration — using traces/logs to disambiguate components at the same level. To decide between MG01 and MG02 we need to confirm which component first showed any metric KPI breach (earliest anomaly across all KPIs) and whether that earliest breach had significant severity and/or multiple KPIs breached simultaneously. This will help identify the true root cause component and precise occurrence time.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using metric.csv, compute global P95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) from the full available series (no time filtering). Then filter metric.csv to the incident window 2021-03-23 06:30:00 → 2021-03-23 07:00:00 (UTC+8) and mark anomaly rows where value >= global_p95. Restrict to components MG01 and MG02. For each component, find the earliest timestamp in the window where any KPI is anomalous and compute: component, earliest_anomaly_ts, number_of_distinct_kpis_anomalous_at_that_ts, the top_kpi_at_that_ts (kpi_name with largest severity_ratio at that timestamp), top_kpi_value, top_kpi_global_p95, top_kpi_severity_ratio. Return exactly two compact records (one per component). Only return these records."
}

